// Lorenz cipher structure
// 12 wheels with varying pin patterns
// Chi wheels: 5 (mixing)
// Psi wheels: 5 (stepping)
// Motor wheels: 2 (controlling)
// 
// Key space: ~10^19 combinations
// Brute force by hand: Impossible
// Statistical analysis: Possible with speed
// 
// Colossus solution:
// Read intercepted tape at 5,000 chars/sec
// Compare against generated patterns
// Count statistical matches electronically

// Colossus Mark I specifications
// Vacuum tubes: 1,500
// Paper tape speed: 5,000 chars/second
// Operations: Boolean logic, counting
// Programmability: Switch/plugboard configuration
// 
// Key innovation:
// Electronic speed + reliability
// Proved vacuum tubes could work at scale

// Colossus specifications
// 
// Mark I: 1,500 tubes
// Mark II: 2,400 tubes
// Tape speed: 5,000 chars/second
// Paper tape: 30 mph through reader
// 
// Reliability secret:
// - High-quality components
// - Continuous operation (no thermal cycling)
// - Redundant designs where possible
// - Careful power supply regulation

// Lorenz cryptanalysis (simplified)
// 
// Cipher = Plaintext XOR Key
// Delta-cipher = Delta-plain XOR Delta-key
// 
// For German text:
// - Certain character pairs are common
// - Delta patterns have statistical bias
// 
// Colossus approach:
// 1. Generate candidate key patterns
// 2. XOR with cipher tape
// 3. Count statistical matches
// 4. High count = likely correct setting
// 
// Speed: millions of tests per hour

// Turing's ACE innovations (1945)
// 
// - Stored program architecture
// - Self-modifying code
// - Subroutine calling conventions
// - Hardware stack (conceptual)
// - Microprogrammed control
// 
// Ahead of its time:
// - Full ACE: never built
// - Pilot ACE: 1950 (simplified)
// - Ideas mainstream: 1960s-1970s
// 
// Turing's vision: too advanced for
// the bureaucracy to understand

